It's impossible to reverse-engineer the Solidity code exactly from a smart contract's bytecode because a lot of the source code information (such as variable names, comments, etc.) gets lost during the compilation process. However, the bytecode can be decompiled to an intermediate representation such as the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) bytecode. Using EVM bytecode, you can see the high-level logic of the contract, but it would still be a long way from the original Solidity code.

Here is an example of a simple Solidity contract:

```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.5.16;

contract SimpleContract {
    uint256 public value;

    function setValue(uint256 _value) public {
        value = _value;
    }

    function getValue() public view returns (uint256) {
        return value;
    }
}
```

But remember, due to the complexity of smart contracts and their bytecode, it's impossible to exactly map bytecode to its original Solidity source code.
